node.text:
On the staircase of my childhood home, there was a photo of my dad and his two brothers; wide smiles, aviator sunglasses, arms draped over each other’s tanned shoulders. They were probably about the age that I am now. They kissed their wives and young kids goodbye and jetted off on the ultimate adventure together, driving down into Mexico to travel the Baja peninsula.

I thought about that photo yesterday morning as I sat at the southernmost tip of that same peninsula, having driven the entirety of it on my own.
At first I wasn’t so sure what this trip was really about for me. I decided to do it approximately 4 days before I got in the car and started doing it.
When I got to the bottom, there was no welcoming party. There was no ribbon I ran through dramatically, arms outstretched in victory. I just sat alone, looking at the Pacific Ocean with a mezcal margarita, a grin on my face, and a patchwork of salt-covered hounds at my feet. 

“Wherever you go, there you are…”
There’s a reason I had my friend Scott engrave that on a necklace for me recently.
If you think that driving far away or disappearing between the palapas of some white sand beach is going to solve all your problems and mend all the shattered parts of you…I hate to disappoint you, but it probably won’t.
The real work, the real change? That has come to me in the parts you don’t see on here. That has come to me in the days when I’ve stopped trying to run from myself. That has come in the weekly therapy sessions. That has come in the ugly parts, the devastating parts, the burned bridges, the learned lessons, the nights alone in the dark when I replayed things over and over and over and sobbed myself to sleep and wished it was different…wished I was different.
There were a lot less palm trees in that process.

I’ve had an incredible time down here because I didn’t come down here to “figure it all out.”
That’s a day by day thing, no matter what stretch of road I’m on or what view is floating by outside my window.
I’m still figuring it all out.
Just…with a slightly better tan now.

Love, your EA 🧡

node.text:
My decision to not have children feels different as a single woman.
And I feel like I need to acknowledge how significant that difference is and how much I admire and honor the single, child-free women who have hurrahed right along with my posts all these years…the posts about how “alone” I felt in that choice, all whilst having a supportive partner beside me.
Well, shit. I’m definitely alone in that choice now.
I still feel beyond secure in it, but I am so much more aware of its consequences.

“Dealbreaker.”
That’s the word that bounces off the walls of my mind. I remember friends scrolling through dating profiles, reading certain details…
Political affiliation: Dealbreaker!
Religious beliefs: Dealbreaker!
Smoker: Dealbreaker!
A woman who does not want children is absolutely a dealbreaker for many potential partners. And that’s understandable.
I would *never* want to deprive someone of such a significant part of the future they’ve imagined for themselves.

And so, the concept of a partner seems a bit further off sometimes, and that has made me question things I’ve never had to before. But my conclusion day after day is that I already know the answer to those questions.

Because night after night, even though I lay down by myself, I sleep well knowing that I’m truly being myself.

node.text:
Yesterday my mom and I were talking on the phone and she was listing off all these big, stressful things and huge potential life changes coming up and all the planning and figuring out she’s gotta do. And then she sighed and said, “…anyway, I’m not gonna let it ruin my afternoon.” 😂 and THAT is the energy 🙏

Also, the stoke is very very high because my mama is coming down to Mexico on Sunday to stay with me for a week 🌴🍹👯‍♀️
